{"title_page": "Sarabande", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n[[File:Zarabanda de la partie III de la Neue Clavier\u00fcbung de Johan Kuhnau.jpg|thumb|A Sarabande in binary form by [[Johann Kuhnau]] {{audio|Zarabanda de la partie III de la Neue Clavier\u00fcbung de Johan Kuhnau.mid|Play}}]]\n\nThe '''sarabande''' (from {{lang-es|zarabanda}}) is a [[dance]] in [[triple metre]].\n\n==History==\nThe dance may have been of Guatemalan and Mexican origin evolved from a Spanish dance with Arab influences, danced with a lively double line of couples with [[castanets]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|date=1990|publisher=The University of Chicago|location=Chicago, Illinois|page=445, Volume 10|edition=15th|format=micropaedia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Concise Garland Encyclopedia of World Music, Volumen1 |publisher=Garland Encyclopedia of World Music |isbn=9780415994033 |pages=230 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ajMsBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA230&lpg=PA230&dq=sarabande+guatemala#v=onepage&q=sarabande%20guatemala&f=false|date=2013-01-11 }}</ref> A dance called ''zarabanda'' is first mentioned in 1539 in [[Central America]] in the poem ''Vida y tiempo de Maricasta\u00f1a'', written in [[Panama]] by Fernando de Guzm\u00e1n Mej\u00eda.<ref name=HudsonLittle2001>Richard Hudson and Meredith Ellis Little, \"[http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.24574 Sarabande]\", Grove Music Online, edited by Deane Root (accessed 6 December 2016).</ref><ref>[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Pitt\u00ed]], ''Panam\u00e1 blues'' (Panama: El Hacedor, 2010): {{Page needed|date=November 2013}}.</ref> The dance seems to have been especially popular in the 16th and 17th centuries, initially in the [[Spanish colonies]], before moving across the Atlantic to [[Spain]].\n\nThe Jesuit priest [[Juan de Mariana]] thought it indecent, describing it in his ''Tratato contra los juegos p\u00fablicos'' (Treatise Against Public Amusements, 1609) as \"a dance and song so loose in its words and so ugly in its motions that it is enough to excite bad emotions in even very decent people\".<ref name=\"Bellingham\">Jane Bellingham, \"Sarabande\", ''The Oxford Companion to Music'', edited by Alison Latham (Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press, 2002).</ref> A character in an [[entrem\u00e9s]] by [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]] alluded to the dance's notoriety by saying that hell was its \"birthplace and breeding place\" (in {{lang-es|origen y principio|links=no}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cervantes|first1=Miguel de|title=Entremeses|year=1615|chapter=Entrem\u00e9s de La Cueva de Salamanca|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JcPBet8vq94C&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=[[Ediciones Akal]]|publication-date=2007|page=184|isbn=8446027992}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=Esses|first1=Maurice|title=Dance and Instrumental ''Diferencias'' in Spain During the 17th and Early 18th Centuries: History and background, music and dance|year=1992|publisher=Pendragon Press|page=742|isbn=0945193084|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_HDx_z2AaIC&pg=PA742#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> It was banned in Spain in 1583 but was nevertheless still performed and frequently cited in literature of the period (for instance, by [[Lope de Vega]]).<ref name=HudsonLittle2001/>\n\nIt spread to [[Italy]] in the 17th century, and to [[France]], where it became a slow court dance.<ref name=\"Bellingham\" />\n\n[[Baroque music]]ians of the 18th century wrote [[Suite (music)|suites of dance music]] written in [[binary form]] that typically included a sarabande as the third of four movements. It was often paired with and followed by a [[Jig (dance)|jig]] or [[gigue]].<ref>Percy A. Scholes (ed.), ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (London and New York: Oxford University Press, 1977), p.&nbsp;911.</ref>  [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J.S. Bach]] sometimes gave the sarabande a privileged place in his music, even outside the context of dance suites; in particular, the theme and climactic 25th variation from his [[Goldberg Variations]] are both sarabandes.\n\nThe anonymous [[harmony|harmonic sequence]] known as ''[[La Folia]]'' appears in pieces of various types, mainly dances, by dozens of composers from the time of [[Alonso Mudarra|Mudarra]] (1546) and [[Arcangelo Corelli|Corelli]] through to the present day.<ref>Giuseppe Gerbino and Alexander Silbiger, \"Folia\", ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (professor of music)|John Tyrrell]] (London: Macmillan Publishers, 2001); Elaine Sisman, \"Variations, \u00a73: Variation Types\", ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by Stanley Sadie and John Tyrrell (London: Macmillan Publishers, 2001).</ref> The theme of the fourth-movement Sarabande of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s [[Keyboard suite in D minor (HWV 437)]] for harpsichord, one of these many pieces, appears prominently in the film ''[[Barry Lyndon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barry-lyndon-music-from-the-soundtrack-mw0000739630|title=Barry Lyndon (music from the soundtrack)|publisher=allmusic.com}}</ref>\n\nThe sarabande was revived in the 19th and early 20th centuries by the German composer [[Louis Spohr]] (in his ''Salonst\u00fccke'', Op. 135 of 1847), Norwegian composer [[Edvard Grieg]] (in his ''[[Holberg Suite]]'' of 1884), French composers such as [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]] and [[Erik Satie|Satie]], and in England, in different styles, [[Ralph Vaughan Williams|Vaughan Williams]] (in ''[[Job: A Masque for Dancing]]''), [[Benjamin Britten]] (in the ''[[Simple Symphony]]''), [[Herbert Howells]] (in ''Six Pieces for Organ: Saraband for the Morning of Easter''), and [[Carlos Ch\u00e1vez]] in the ballet ''[[La hija de C\u00f3lquide]]''.\n\nThe sarabande inspired the title of [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s last film ''[[Saraband]]'' (2003). The film uses the sarabande from J. S. Bach's Fifth [[Cello Suites (Bach)|Cello Suite]], which Bergman also used in ''[[Cries and Whispers]]'' (1971).<ref>''[http://www.ingmarbergman.se/page.asp?guid=1242C45B-C66B-4975-A018-5CD2CA55BFF8 Ingmar Bergman Saraband \u2013 Sources of inspiration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224835/http://www.ingmarbergman.se/page.asp?guid=1242C45B-C66B-4975-A018-5CD2CA55BFF8 |date=2007-09-27 }}''</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Carvajal, Mara Lioba Juan. 2007. ''La zarabanda: pluralidad y controversia de un g\u00e9nero musical''. Arte y expresi\u00f3n. [Zacatecas, Mexico]: Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Zacatecas, Programa Integral de Fortalecimiento Institucional; M\u00e9xico, D.F.: Plaza y Vald\u00e9s. {{ISBN|978-970-722-562-6}}.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Stevenson |first1=Robert |title=The First Dated Mention of the Sarabande |journal=Journal of the American Musicological Society |volume=5 |issue=1 |year=1952 |pages=29\u201331 |doi=10.2307/829447 |jstor=829447 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Whittall |first1=Arnold |title=Resisting Tonality: Tippett, Beethoven and the Sarabande |journal=Music Analysis |volume=9 |issue=3 |year=1990 |pages=267\u201386 |doi=10.2307/853980 |jstor=853980 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Howat |first1=Roy |title=Debussy, masques, l'isle joyeuseand a lost sarabande |journal=Musicology Australia |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=1987 |pages=16\u201330 |doi=10.1080/08145857.1987.10415177 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Louwenaar-Lueck |first1=Karyl |title=The sequence of sarabande and air in Bach's keyboard partitas |journal=Bach |volume=23 |issue=1 |year=1992 |pages=38\u201350 |jstor=41640369 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Saraband}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=judV76gLib0 Video \u2013 basic steps of the Sarabande]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pusyM49Wwjo Video \u2013 solo Sarabande performed by Kaspar Mainz, music by Charles Dieupart, with Il Giardino Armonico]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GjLTTgv5FUQ Video \u2013 Baroque Sarabande \u00e0 deux]\n* [http://www.early-dance.de/en/content/6381-sarabande-deux Choreography \u2013 step plan of the above \"Sarabande \u00e0 deux\" (Feuillet, 1704)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080527143749/http://www.streetswing.com/histmain/z3sarbn1.htm Streetswing.com Dance History Archives]\n\n{{Baroque dance}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Baroque dance]]\n[[Category:Baroque music]]\n[[Category:Spanish Baroque]]\n[[Category:Triple time dances]]\n[[Category:Spanish dances]]\n[[Category:Spanish music]]\n[[Category:Dance forms in classical music]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n[[File:Zarabanda de la partie III de la Neue Clavier\u00fcbung de Johan Kuhnau.jpg|thumb|A Sarabande in binary form by [[Johann Kuhnau]] {{audio|Zarabanda de la partie III de la Neue Clavier\u00fcbung de Johan Kuhnau.mid|Play}}]]\n\nThe '''sarabande''' (from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''zarabanda'') is a [[dance]] in [[triple metre]].\n\n==History==\nThe dance may have been of Guatemalan and Mexican origin evolved from a Spanish dance with Arab influences, danced with a lively double line of couples with [[castanets]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|date=1990|publisher=The University of Chicago|location=Chicago, Illinois|page=445, Volume 10|edition=15th|format=micropaedia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Concise Garland Encyclopedia of World Music, Volumen1 |publisher=Garland Encyclopedia of World Music |isbn=9780415994033 |pages=230 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ajMsBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA230&lpg=PA230&dq=sarabande+guatemala#v=onepage&q=sarabande%20guatemala&f=false|date=2013-01-11 }}</ref> A dance called ''zarabanda'' is first mentioned in 1539 in [[Central America]] in the poem ''Vida y tiempo de Maricasta\u00f1a'', written in [[Panama]] by Fernando de Guzm\u00e1n Mej\u00eda.<ref name=HudsonLittle2001>Richard Hudson and Meredith Ellis Little, \"[http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.24574 Sarabande]\", Grove Music Online, edited by Deane Root (accessed 6 December 2016).</ref><ref>[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Pitt\u00ed]], ''Panam\u00e1 blues'' (Panama: El Hacedor, 2010): {{Page needed|date=November 2013}}.</ref> The dance seems to have been especially popular in the 16th and 17th centuries, initially in the [[Spanish colonies]], before moving across the Atlantic to [[Spain]].\n\nThe Jesuit priest [[Juan de Mariana]] thought it indecent, describing it in his ''Tratato contra los juegos p\u00fablicos'' (Treatise Against Public Amusements, 1609) as \"a dance and song so loose in its words and so ugly in its motions that it is enough to excite bad emotions in even very decent people\".<ref name=\"Bellingham\">Jane Bellingham, \"Sarabande\", ''The Oxford Companion to Music'', edited by Alison Latham (Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press, 2002).</ref> A character in an [[entrem\u00e9s]] by [[Miguel de Cervantes|Cervantes]] alluded to the dance's notoriety by saying that hell was its \"birthplace and breeding place\" (in {{lang-es|origen y principio|links=no}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cervantes|first1=Miguel de|title=Entremeses|year=1615|chapter=Entrem\u00e9s de La Cueva de Salamanca|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JcPBet8vq94C&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=[[Ediciones Akal]]|publication-date=2007|page=184|isbn=8446027992}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=Esses|first1=Maurice|title=Dance and Instrumental ''Diferencias'' in Spain During the 17th and Early 18th Centuries: History and background, music and dance|year=1992|publisher=Pendragon Press|page=742|isbn=0945193084|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_HDx_z2AaIC&pg=PA742#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> It was banned in Spain in 1583 but was nevertheless still performed and frequently cited in literature of the period (for instance, by [[Lope de Vega]]).<ref name=HudsonLittle2001/>\n\nIt spread to [[Italy]] in the 17th century, and to [[France]], where it became a slow court dance.<ref name=\"Bellingham\" />\n\n[[Baroque music]]ians of the 18th century wrote [[Suite (music)|suites of dance music]] written in [[binary form]] that typically included a sarabande as the third of four movements. It was often paired with and followed by a [[Jig (dance)|jig]] or [[gigue]].<ref>Percy A. Scholes (ed.), ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (London and New York: Oxford University Press, 1977), p.&nbsp;911.</ref>  [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J.S. Bach]] sometimes gave the sarabande a privileged place in his music, even outside the context of dance suites; in particular, the theme and climactic 25th variation from his [[Goldberg Variations]] are both sarabandes.\n\nThe anonymous [[harmony|harmonic sequence]] known as ''[[La Folia]]'' appears in pieces of various types, mainly dances, by dozens of composers from the time of [[Alonso Mudarra|Mudarra]] (1546) and [[Arcangelo Corelli|Corelli]] through to the present day.<ref>Giuseppe Gerbino and Alexander Silbiger, \"Folia\", ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (professor of music)|John Tyrrell]] (London: Macmillan Publishers, 2001); Elaine Sisman, \"Variations, \u00a73: Variation Types\", ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by Stanley Sadie and John Tyrrell (London: Macmillan Publishers, 2001).</ref> The theme of the fourth-movement Sarabande of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s [[Keyboard suite in D minor (HWV 437)]] for harpsichord, one of these many pieces, appears prominently in the film ''[[Barry Lyndon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barry-lyndon-music-from-the-soundtrack-mw0000739630|title=Barry Lyndon (music from the soundtrack)|publisher=allmusic.com}}</ref>\n\nThe sarabande was revived in the 19th and early 20th centuries by the German composer [[Louis Spohr]] (in his ''Salonst\u00fccke'', Op. 135 of 1847), Norwegian composer [[Edvard Grieg]] (in his ''[[Holberg Suite]]'' of 1884), French composers such as [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]] and [[Erik Satie|Satie]], and in England, in different styles, [[Ralph Vaughan Williams|Vaughan Williams]] (in ''[[Job: A Masque for Dancing]]''), [[Benjamin Britten]] (in the ''[[Simple Symphony]]''), [[Herbert Howells]] (in ''Six Pieces for Organ: Saraband for the Morning of Easter''), and [[Carlos Ch\u00e1vez]] in the ballet ''[[La hija de C\u00f3lquide]]''.\n\nThe sarabande inspired the title of [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s last film ''[[Saraband]]'' (2003). The film uses the sarabande from J. S. Bach's Fifth [[Cello Suites (Bach)|Cello Suite]], which Bergman also used in ''[[Cries and Whispers]]'' (1971).<ref>''[http://www.ingmarbergman.se/page.asp?guid=1242C45B-C66B-4975-A018-5CD2CA55BFF8 Ingmar Bergman Saraband \u2013 Sources of inspiration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224835/http://www.ingmarbergman.se/page.asp?guid=1242C45B-C66B-4975-A018-5CD2CA55BFF8 |date=2007-09-27 }}''</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Carvajal, Mara Lioba Juan. 2007. ''La zarabanda: pluralidad y controversia de un g\u00e9nero musical''. Arte y expresi\u00f3n. [Zacatecas, Mexico]: Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Zacatecas, Programa Integral de Fortalecimiento Institucional; M\u00e9xico, D.F.: Plaza y Vald\u00e9s. {{ISBN|978-970-722-562-6}}.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Stevenson |first1=Robert |title=The First Dated Mention of the Sarabande |journal=Journal of the American Musicological Society |volume=5 |issue=1 |year=1952 |pages=29\u201331 |doi=10.2307/829447 |jstor=829447 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Whittall |first1=Arnold |title=Resisting Tonality: Tippett, Beethoven and the Sarabande |journal=Music Analysis |volume=9 |issue=3 |year=1990 |pages=267\u201386 |doi=10.2307/853980 |jstor=853980 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Howat |first1=Roy |title=Debussy, masques, l'isle joyeuseand a lost sarabande |journal=Musicology Australia |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=1987 |pages=16\u201330 |doi=10.1080/08145857.1987.10415177 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Louwenaar-Lueck |first1=Karyl |title=The sequence of sarabande and air in Bach's keyboard partitas |journal=Bach |volume=23 |issue=1 |year=1992 |pages=38\u201350 |jstor=41640369 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Saraband}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=judV76gLib0 Video \u2013 basic steps of the Sarabande]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pusyM49Wwjo Video \u2013 solo Sarabande performed by Kaspar Mainz, music by Charles Dieupart, with Il Giardino Armonico]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GjLTTgv5FUQ Video \u2013 Baroque Sarabande \u00e0 deux]\n* [http://www.early-dance.de/en/content/6381-sarabande-deux Choreography \u2013 step plan of the above \"Sarabande \u00e0 deux\" (Feuillet, 1704)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080527143749/http://www.streetswing.com/histmain/z3sarbn1.htm Streetswing.com Dance History Archives]\n\n{{Baroque dance}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Baroque dance]]\n[[Category:Baroque music]]\n[[Category:Spanish Baroque]]\n[[Category:Triple time dances]]\n[[Category:Spanish dances]]\n[[Category:Spanish music]]\n[[Category:Dance forms in classical music]]\n", "name_user": "OwenBlacker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Language tagging", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarabande"}
